<HEADLINE>
<P>
GREAT INVENTIONS/GOOD INTENTIONS: AN ILLUSTRATED HISTORY OF AMERICAN PATENT 
DESIGNS BY ERIC BAKER, TEXT BY JANE MARTIN (CHRONICLE: 16.95). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Charles Solomon 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although highly entertaining, "Great Inventions" is just a portfolio of patent 
drawings from the '30s and '40s, rather than a history of design. 
</P>
<P>
The influence of Modernism can be seen in the emphasis on streamlining and the 
illusion of speed in these drawings: Even the ashtrays have had their corners 
smoothed away until they resemble sleek dirigibles. A surprising number of 
these drawings look like something else: A radio becomes a miniature grand 
piano, and a hilarious design for an Americana restaurant combines a log cabin 
with a covered wagon. Only a few of these projects were ever realized -- and no 
wonder. Charles Solomon 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA123090-0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 328924 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 30, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 10; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
212 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Charles Solomon 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HOBBIT by J. R. R. Tolkien, illustrated by David Wenzel, adapted by Charles 
Dixon with Sean Deming (Eclipse: $12.95). "The Hobbit" remains both the 
simplest and most problematic of J. R. R. Tolkien's works. 
</P>
<P>
Although it serves as a prelude to "The Lord of the Rings," "The Hobbit" 
remains a children's story that lacks the epic sweep of the later trilogy. 
David Wenzel, Charles Dixon and Sean Deming turn this charming tale into a 
rather stodgy Classics Comic, peopled with wooden figures. Elrond and Gandalf 
lack the requisite otherwordly majesty; Thranduil, the king of Wood-Elves, 
looks like a podgy bishop in a bad historic film, and their red-nosed version 
of Bilbo Baggins fails to convey the proper aura of British coziness. None of 
the characters emerge as individuals: Gandalf and all the Dwarfs are drawn with 
similar beards and costumes, so it's difficult to tell them apart. There have 
been numerous attempts to depict Middle Earth, including the calendars of the 
Hildebrandts and the regrettable films of Ralph Bakshi and Rankin-Bass. They've 
all failed because Tolkien's prose isn't visually oriented: It should be read 
-- or better yet, chanted -- around a campfire, like the medieval sagas that 
inspired it. Charles Solomon 
</P>
</TEXT>
