<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 59; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
197 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLA BREVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WALTER PRICE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jose Carreras, Placido Domingo, Luciano Pavarotti In Concert: Arias and songs. 
Orchestras of the Florence May Festival and Rome Opera, Zubin Mehta, 
conducting. 
</P>
<P>
London 430 433-2 (compact disc). In July, three of the most famous tenors in 
the world, along with a well-known conductor, participated in one of the most 
extravagant vocal three-ring circuses in memory. This recording is taken from 
that evening and has not one shred of interest for a serious collector. Chief 
curiosity is the state of Carreras' voice after his long battle with leukemia. 
The sound is fresh and youthful, if there are hints of a wobble in high, 
fortissimo passages. Domingo's singing is about as usual, which means generally 
beautiful, if unvarying in color or expressivity. It is left to Pavarotti to 
provide the one instance of distinguished singing in a Crescenzo song, "Rondine 
al Nido." As always, he projects the Italian language with a mastery few 
singers can match. The final medley of war horses reaches its height of 
vulgarity with a unison "Vincero" at the close of "Nessun dorma." Why a serious 
musician like Mehta would lend his name to this travesty is an open 
question.WALTER PRICE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA123090-0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 328934 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 30, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
