<HEADLINE>
<P>
THAI BONES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kathie Jenkins 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When you have a gnawing hunger for Thai food . . . 
</P>
<P>
Lannathai Restaurant, 4457 Van Nuys Blvd., Sherman Oaks. (818) 995-0808. Style: 
Tried-and-true -- offers all the old favorites. 
</P>
<P>
Setting: Fancy with kidney-shaped swimming pool, large brass deer with real 
antlers and a Buddhist shrine. Recommended: Stuffed chicken wings, $7.50. 
</P>
<P>
Kim Tar, 4806 Melrose Ave., Los Angeles. (213) 669-1180. Style: Barbecue stand 
specializing in the foods of the Chiu Chow -- Chinese from Thailand. Setting: 
No frills. Recommended: Fried hen, $5.50; barbecued spareribs, $4. 
</P>
<P>
Pi Yai Restaurant, 5757 Hollywood Blvd., Hollywood. (213) 462-0292. Style: Cafe 
offering Isaan dishes -- food from Thailand's northeastern provinces. Setting: 
Beige and linoleum. Recommended: Stewed pork hock over rice, $3.95. 
</P>
<P>
Talesai, 9043 Sunset Blvd., West Hollywood. (213) 275-9724. Style: Tiny tidbits 
of tantalizing Thai. Setting: Arty. Recommended: Barbecued spareribs, $7.95. 
</P>
<P>
Thai House, 8657 W. Pico Blvd., Los Angeles. (213) 274-5492. Style: Alienation, 
Bohemian-style. Setting: Heavy on the metal. Recommended: Barbecued spareribs, 
$7.50. Kathie Jenkins 
</P>
</TEXT>
