<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: VENICE ART TEACHER WRITES BOOK ABOUT MURALS -- IN FRENCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRISTINA V. GODBEY Items for People can be mailed to People, Los Angeles 
Times, Suite 200, 1717 4th St., Santa Monica 90401. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Marco Elliot, a commercial arts teacher at Venice High School, is the author of 
a how-to guide on street murals, written in French. 
</P>
<P>
Elliot, a native of Cannes, France, used his experiences as an artist and 
teacher to write "Le Pied du Mur." The book describes the mural-making process 
for everyone from kindergarten children to young adults. It also explains how 
damaged murals are repaired and details the history of murals. 
</P>
<P>
Several photographs of Elliot's own works are featured in the book, along with 
works of other artists from the Los Angeles area and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
"In the early 1980s, I devoted several years to doing street murals in the 
south of France," Elliot said. "I was commissioned by the city of Cannes to do 
something with an environmental theme, and I did a mural on air pollution. 
</P>
<P>
"An artist's mind is always open to people and problems," he said, "but it's 
sometimes difficult to work in urban settings because of noise, traffic and 
pollution." 
</P>
<P>
University High School student Carlo Mattoni attained the highest overall 
individual score in this year's Los Angeles Unified School District's Academic 
Decathalon competition. 
</P>
<P>
He scored 8,233 points in the 10-category competition. He also won the Fine 
Arts category and received a $1,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
Virginia Randolph, head librarian for public services at Pepperdine 
University's Payson Library, has been appointed to the the Extended Campus 
Library Service Committee of the American Library Assn. 
</P>
<P>
Randolph, who was selected for inclusion in "Who's Who in Library and 
Information Science," will work with the national committee to evaluate 
information-delivery systems for off-campus programs. 
</P>
<P>
She is also involved with the bibliographic instruction section of the Assn. of 
College and Research Libraries. 
</P>
<P>
City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky has presented a certificate of appreciation to 
Alfreda Iglehart, a Los Angeles Marathon volunteer. 
</P>
<P>
Iglehart, an associate professor of social welfare at UCLA, is the marathon's 
liaison with national track clubs. 
</P>
<P>
She is also a marathoner and won the 1990 Santa Monica Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
The UCLA Alumni Assn.'s Advisory and Scholarship Program has awarded 
scholarships to Joseph Doherty of Los Angeles and Lise Hilboldt of Santa 
Monica. 
</P>
<P>
Doherty and Hilboldt both attended Santa Monica College before transferring to 
UCLA. Each will receive a $2,500 community college scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
Scholarships are given to students who have a minimum 3.5 grade-point average 
in community college course work and junior standing upon entering UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Monica High School senior Alicia Roberts has been recognized for 
outstanding performance in writing by the National Council of Teachers of 
English. 
</P>
<P>
She is one of more than 800 winners of a 1990 Achievement Award. 
</P>
<P>
Sinai Akiba Academy will honor Tooran Mahboubi at the school's 1991 Benefit 
Dinner Dance on Jan. 19. Mahboubi will be recognized for her leadership in the 
Jewish and Persian communities. She founded the Bel-Air Chapter of Na'amat 
U.S.A. and has been president the past 10 years. CHRISTINA V. GODBEY Items for 
People can be mailed to People, Los Angeles Times, Suite 200, 1717 4th St., 
Santa Monica 90401. 
</P>
</TEXT>
